recordings.rmk: Clean recording, no editing other than trimming ends.  Small island in the Yukon of mostly medium sized willows.  The willows had been defoliated by some type of caterpillars which I'd been seeing off and on along much of the River.  These birds were worked up because I was wandering around trying to get fox sparrow recordings.  Sounds like at least 3 birds in this recording.  At least one male.  The rest are unknown.  It seemed like birds in general were singing later in the summer than normal.  I theorized that it had something to do with all the caterpillars (although they had vanished at this point and did not seem to turn into anything).  Hot, muggy (80+F), calm.

Natural sound. Bird was foraging on the ground in the forest understory, occasionally perching on limbs and stumps ~1m above the ground to sing. 

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800 Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

recordings.loc: Bluebonnet Swamp, East Baton Rouge Parish, Louisiana
recordings.rmk: Six calls while handheld (cuts heavily edited to remove talking, etc.), and two after release, from a bird that was only discovered to be wintering at this site the day before. It was intermediate in many characters between Gray-cheeked and Bicknell's (it was extensively measured while in the hand), but had a dingy mandible, very long primary extension, and the call notes (especially the penultimate in this recording, after release) seem to be vaguely more Gray-cheeked-like than Bicknell's-like (Bicknell's would be a state first). I should note that the bird's presence as a wintering bird is almost certainly due to missing its left foot.

Recording trimmed and reduced frequencies below 1000 khz and above 6000 khz.  Rather poor recording of GCTH overhead in low clouds as a nocturnal migrant.  Spring flights not nearly as dense with thrushes as fall flights (at least from this location) so this bird was a bit of a surprise.

Homemade flowerpot microphone used, sound quality not great.  Over 65 Gray-cheeked Thrush calls recorded this night.  Recording made with Olympus LS-10S, trimmed to about 2-7 khz, and amplified by 5.
